    <text>
        <body>
             <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" resp="#POC" source="MAC1945"><!--update lang and resp here-->              
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><persName><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="stroke"/> <w type="formula" lemma="maqqas">ᚋᚐᚊᚔ</w> <w type="formula" lemma="muccoviias">ᚋᚒᚉᚑᚔ</w> 
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:down"/><name nymRef="#?">ᚔᚃᚑᚇᚐᚉᚉᚐ</name></persName>
                </ab> 
            </div>                    
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" xml:space="preserve" resp="#POC" source="MAC1945">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><persName><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="stroke"/> <w type="formula" lemma="maqqas">MAQI</w> <w type="formula" lemma="muccoviias">MUCOI</w> 
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:down"/><name nymRef="#?">IVODACCA</name></persName>
                </ab>
                <ab type="list">[---] MAQI MUCOI IVODACCA</ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                <app n="1">
<note>The above reading of the inscription is supplied by Macalister (1945, 265). When Atkinson (1884, 308-309) examined the stone, traces of the concluding letters of the first name remained and were read as -DI. Atkinson (1884, 309) also maintained that there is a feathermark following IVODACCA, which he read in the opposite direction (ANSALOTI) but Macalister dismissed this.</note>                    
                </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>of ... son of the kindred of ?</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                 <p>The inscription contains the common formula words MAQI (Old Irish <distinct xml:lang="sga"><ref target="https://dil.ie/31166">mac, macc</ref></distinct> 'son') and MUCOI (see Stifter 2025. MUCOI did not survive into the later language but related to <distinct xml:lang="sga"><ref target="https://dil.ie/31187">maccu, moccu</ref></distinct> 'belonging to the family of'.</p>
            </div>
